{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"886c9fd3-af01-4215-b4f3-61adeb1bc094","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it re-runs tests automatically whenever you save a file. To focus on just the failing test:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThis watches for changes, rebuilds, and re-runs that single test on each save.\n\n**About the bug:** `RemoveStock` never validates quantity — it just subtracts. You need to throw when `quantity > available`. Fix line 37 in `InventoryServiceTests.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException(\"Insufficient stock\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nWant me to apply the fix so you can verify it with `dotnet watch test`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"82faad71-7f37-4155-af5d-729f014181fe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. With .NET and Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as configured in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` to get hot reload for tests.\n\nActually, with the newer Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner, the way to do hot reload is via `dotnet test --hotreload` which was introduced more recently, or `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me check what's available. With .NET 10 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet watch test` should work. But there's also a newer feature specifically for test hot reload.\n\n\nFor rapid iteration, `dotnet watch test` is the most straightforward approach—it watches for file changes and automatically reruns the tests. I can suggest this command and optionally show how to filter to a specific failing test if needed.","outputTokens":432,"requestId":"0830:1F4026:D1556E:F356CD:69EAC816"},"id":"77ebe8ff-1385-42c6-bb22-362a50c7a96c","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:32:17.222Z","parentId":"1cf54888-e51a-4954-a17d-b7df11c6ee6d"}
